title: For Sale:  INERT-M2-A2 LAW TUBE
postcontent:
M72-series LAW is a lightweight, self-contained, antiarmor weapon consisting of a rocket packed in a launcher (Figure 2-1). It is man-portable, may be fired from either shoulder, and is issued as a round of ammunition. It requires little from the user— only a visual inspection and some operator maintenance. The launcher, which consists of two tubes, one inside the other, serves as a watertight packing container for the rocket and houses a percussion-type firing mechanism that activates the rocket.
. Outer Tube. The trigger housing assembly (which contains the trigger assembly) is on the upper surface of the outer tube. So are the trigger arming handle, front and rear sight assemblies, and the launcher's rear cover.

b. Inner Tube. The inner tube telescopes outward toward the rear, guided by a channel assembly that rides in an alignment slot in the outer tube's trigger housing assembly. The channel assembly also houses the firing pin rod assembly, which includes a detent lever assembly. The detent lever assembly moves under the trigger assembly in the outer tube, locking the inner tube in the extended position and cocking the weapon. All this must occur before the weapon can be fired.

THERE IS NO ROCKET.  Once the rocket is fired. the Tube is thrown away. It cannot be re-loaded.  Again for nervous types. This is an EMPTY TUBE. Bought Surplus at a gun show a few years ago.  Makes a great display piece on a wall.  

No license or anything required to purchase this empty tube.
This is a nice one. It has the front cover and when you expand it. The aiming system pops up.

This particular gun was made in 1942 at the Izhevsk Mechanical Plant (Russian: Ижевский Mеханический Завод, Izhevsky Mekhanchesky Zavod) or IZHMEKH (ИЖМЕХ) was a major firearms manufacturer founded in Izhevsk in 1942 for manufacturing small arms for WWII.

postcontent: Kel Tec PMR-30 semi auto pistol in .22 Mag. This auction is for the actual pistol shown in the photos. Factory new, in the box with all paperwork. Green frame, comes with two magazines. The PMR-30 is a light weight, full size pistol chambered for the flat-shooting .22Magnum cartridge (.22WMR). The PMR-30 operates on a unique hybrid blowback/locked-breech system. This operation system allows for the use of a wide variety of ammunition as it seamlessly adjusts between locked breach and blowback operation, depending on the pressure of the cartridge. It uses a double stack magazine of a new design that holds 30 rounds and fits completely in the grip of the pistol. The trigger is a crisp single action with an over-travel stop. The manual safety is a thumb activated ambidextrous safety lever (up for SAFE, down for FIRE). The slide locks back after the last shot and a manual slide lock lever is also provided. The light, crisp trigger pull and fiber optic sights make the PMR-30 ideal for target shooting and hunting small game. title: For Sale:  British Enfield No. 2, Mark 1 Revolver- 1940 C&R
postcontent:
Type: Double Action (Mark 1) or Double Action Only (Mark 1* and Mark 1**) Chamber: .38/200 (.38S&W) Weight unloaded: 765 g Length: 260 mm Barrel length: 127 mm Capacity: 6 rounds revolver was developed at the Royal Small Arms Factory in Enfield in 1926 – 1927. The design is based on scaled down Webley Mark 6 “break-top” frame, with cylinder chambered for 6 .38/200 rounds. The hammer/trigger group was redesigned, with manual hammer safety lock added, and with separate cylinder lock. This revolver was adopted for British Military service in 1932 as Enfield revolver, .38 caliber, No.2 Mark 1. After 1938, almost all No.2 Mk1s were converted into No.2 Mark 1* configuration. Enfield No.2 Mark 1* were developed in the late 1930s for British Tank Corps, and are distinguished from early Mark 1 by spurless, Double Action Only hammers, lighter mainsprings, and re-shaped grip side plates. The spurless DAO hammers were required by Tank Corps command to avoid snagging the hammers on tank internals. Enfield No.2 Mark 1** appeared in the 1942 as a simplified, wartime design. These guns were similar to No.2 Mark 1*, but without the hammer stop. After the 1945, all those revolvers were recalled and converted into No.2 Mark 1* configuration. 

I am selling to fund another project.

Face to Face only . No shipping. No Trades. I will accept a C&R holder or if you do not have one then if you have a NH Pistol Permit & License (So I can know you are allowed to own guns) Or We do transfer at Collectible Arms and Ammo in Merrimack and we split the $20 transfer fee. title: For Sale:  Custom 1911
postcontent:
This was an R1, but it’s been completely reworked into a bullseye gun. I fit an Ed Brown match grade barrel and bushing. It locks tight enough into the slide that the recoil lugs click and lock into battery with zero movement whatsoever. I polished the barrel throat and feed ramps, along with fitting the barrel hood. I fit a Wilson Combat barrel link (#4 I believe) and grinded it to a perfect fit. I polished the extractor and refit it. I changed the angle of the ejector for perfect ejections every time. I stoned the sear and adjusted the trigger pull to 4 ½ pounds with no creep. I filed the hammer for perfect contact with sear. I crowned the barrel to 11 degrees and reamed it for perfect headspace. I fit a new safety and it functions very crisp and cleanly. I also hot salt blued the gun on 6/26/14. 

This is a series 80 gun, but I milled a spacer out of 10/18 steel to convert it to a standard series 70. I’ll sell it as a series 80, but I’ll include the spacer for conversion. This gun is a must buy for any bullseye shooter who wants a well-priced match grade gun. I know you'll be happy with this gun.

title: For Sale:  Free Advice on Trading.  No Refunds.
location: Right next to your Mangina, Charlotte, North Carolina
postcontent:
I love many things about Armslist.  In particular, I revere the utter humility I experience upon entering into negotiations with some who only knows their particular firearm should sell/trade somewhere between the amount they paid for it at retail, and eleventy-billion dollars (11-tee, 000,000,000 USD).  This is a number one of my friends in high school made up years ago, and it remains my adopted, standard expression for a stupidly high amount of money.  

The hints of this negotiating style are subtle, but follow me on this journey to enlightenment.  It will be just like Back to the Future, except you won’t meet your older mom, dad, or sister's self and Biff is just some guy who doesn’t know how to value guns.  Besides that it’s exactly the same, but Doc isn’t warning you not to change things, and you won't assimilate yourself into doo-wop culture because you slammed some reefer addict's hand in a 56 Belair's door and then have to play four chords of Earth Angel before ripping off Chuck Berry with an Eddie van Halen audio-over.  Still, the similarities are striking.  I share with you the tactics of the masters of this domain:

Tactics (In no particular order)

Tactic # 1: The ubiquitous “Offer” price.

This lets you know that no matter how much you offer, it won’t be enough.  A Glock 19 with an “offer” price tag?  Never fear the uncertainty associated with not using numerical values or specified currencies to indicate desired prices:  You can simply give him double the amount of retail and all the displeasures of private sales can be avoided.  If you offer any less, he will be offended, or as this author has previously coined Armslist related offer offense injury outcomes: “butthurt.”

I imagine each of you has read, memorized, and had reminder notes tattooed inside your armpits the secretive strategies and procedures outlined in the “Proposed Armslist Legislation” posting circulated on here some months ago.  So when individuals get butthurt, you know what to do.  The revised legislation sets forth that you should deploy a “hurt feelings report” and a loading dose of Midol.   Since many of you do not carry those items or possess the wherewithal to deploy them via wireless internet connections, paying double retail is the next best thing to keep the seller from getting Nutella in his man-panties.

Tactic #2:  The fabled “A + B = that gun I really really want.” 

In this trading scenario, the other individual has two guns he wishes to dispose of in order to obtain another one.  Usually this means two out of production long guns for a current production handgun. While nice guns in their own right, these long guns do not sell individually at retail, on the used market, or in the grey market at nearly fifty percent of the used value of the object that “Mr. A+B” desires.  Gun A and Gun B may sell used at around 150 to 200 dollars apiece, far more than the pawn shop would give them.  These fine single shot rifles or entry level shotguns are great to buy at a fair price and use; in fact I would like to buy some of them just to knock around or tinker with.  But they do not command the price of a Glock, XDS, or Dillon Mini-gun.  Nevertheless, notice that when the powers of Gun A and Gun B are combined into a single unified force (not unlike those rings on the old Captain Planet cartoons which harnessed earth, wind, fire, water and heart), they are force to be reckoned with.  At this point, your higher value pistol has been devalued to two entry level long guns.  Should you resist this devaluation, “Mr. A+B” will entice you with odd things such as airsoft or gaming systems.  Just think, instead of owning a handgun you paid retail for, you could trade it for two deer killers which you won’t use because you’re addicted to playing Sonic the Hedgehog.

Tactic #3:  The tactic of “I admit I don’t know about what you have on trade offer, but it ain’t as good as mine….so I’m gonna need some more cash on it/I’m gonna have to have a range day (at your expense of time and money) before I can comment on this matter any further.”

That title may have explained itself.  You notice a gun you want, such as a Glock.  Everyone knows Glock.  I get it.  Great guns, no explanation needed if you’re reading this.  However, it is not the only decent brand.  If it was, no one would list them on here!  I won’t get into what is “best.”  The best is the most reliable one you have in the next 10 seconds.  But when you offer some Glock owners (but not limited to Glock owners, thus I’m not hating on you Austro-philes) an FN or CZ on trade to do an even swap, they employ the tactic of “I don’t know much about your type of gun, so it’ll be an even swap plus 150.”  The even cuter version of this is “We’re way apart on money (on top of your gun).”  And when you ask “how far are we off, ” the comment is “I don’t know” or “I’d need you to take me and your gun to the range before I could name a number.”  This is where I might advise them to simply say, “Never heard of it, thanks but no thanks.”  This is also where I might say, “I’d buy you a beer to talk this over, but you’d probably drown.”  

	So here we have three arguments for simply looking up MSRPs on the guns people are offering and paying double to avoid these types of projectile diarrhea inducing negotiations.  However, if you enjoy not trading or buying the conditions are suitable for you to lose or grey your hair along with increasing your overall stress levels.  This should be an enjoyable hobby, sport, collection, or whatever you call you amassing of arms and munitions.  No matter what you call it, I support it and hope we can overcome the silliness and emotional treatment that many people insist on giving the sale, buying and trading of these sorts of items.

If you encounter theses types of of folks, feel free to trade guns where they hammer you and make money off of you (and vice versa)  But I beg you, don't take their guns in trade for MREs.  It will just prolong the problem for another generation.
